<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-232-149 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 379 890</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  Feb 1991 v2 n2 p44(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Macweek 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cleaner Windows. (debugging Microsoft Windows 3.0)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lockwood, Russ.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.1 (Graphical user interface) (Productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     DebuggingGraphical User InterfaceDisk CachingHard DiskDevice Drivers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CLEANER WINDOWS Though Microsoft Corp. refuses to discuss a timetable orupgrade pricing for Windows 3.1's release, the new version will resolve anobscure bug that causes the interface to lock up when used with IDE-stylehard drives.andM;Microsoft's group product manager, Rich Abel, says that Microsoft'sSmart-Drive disk cache utility conflicts with disk partitioning schemes usedby Ontrack's Disk Manager and Golden Bow's SpeedStor utilities--that is, ifyou're creating a partition greater than 32MB on drives with more than 1,024cylinders.andM;This specific alignment of variables causes a conflict in the BIOS support,leading to a locked system.andP;  The new version of Windows reportedly will beable to sense this alignment and disable the SmartDrive utilityautomatically.andM;Abel also notes that Microsoft released a Windows Supplemental Driver diskthis past October that contains improved and new device drivers for 80printers and 20 displays, including color printers, Super VGA graphicsboards, and graphics boards incorporating the Texas Instruments 34010 and34020 chips.andP;  Microsoft expects to release additional driver disks three tofour times a year.andM;You can obtain the Supplemental Driver disk directly from Microsoft, ordownload the specific driver you need from CompuServe.andO;</TEXT></DOC>